Turns out the President-Eject is not the only high-level US official willing to sacrifice the US national interest for a short-term ego jolt. In America anybody can grow up to be stupid. Kinda makes you proud.

People are following the plane, callsign SPAR19. It's on course for Taiwan, apparently heading in from the east rather than from the Taiwan Strait out of an abundance of caution. Setting this at 100% for now, will revisit later if there's a change of course.
This would be defiant to China and increase tensions between US and China.
She can visit but not mention anything. She could not make it out. She could imply she visited but not say so. She could pull out last minute. Definitely not a certain thing in my judgement.
USS aircraft carrier in vicinity. Hmm.
Just on the back of devleopments
It's 6am local time, Tuesday morning. She's getting there by Tuesday evening

Press out with news that people familiar with the matter are saying that N. Pelosi will be visiting Taiwan. Her intenten seems set.
leaving 4% for last minute cancellation

Maybe she will be loud about it after all... Media reports Nancy Pelosi will indeed visit #Taiwan on her Asian "trip to nowhere."

"Pelosi’s travel plans, like those of most lawmakers, are typically kept under wraps until after leaving a particular country. Yet the public jostling over this particular trip has put immense pressure on the speaker to follow through with a stop in Taiwan, despite China’s increasingly belligerent threats and the Biden administration’s concerns."
I am temporally upping this on more and more breaking news. We can continue to expect the DOD and Department of State to keep trying to convince her to not go. It might be futile at this point.
Press out with news that people familiar with the matter are saying that N. Pelosi will be visiting Taiwan.
https://www.cnn.com/2022/08/01/politics/nancy-pelosi-taiwan-visit/index.html

Updating based on WSJ reporting as well. Still not sure if high attention to this headline will cause a security situation to develop to the point where Pelosi has to cancel her trip there - if reports are true. Nonetheless, the incentives are there, the consistency with Pelosi's style of going after something is there, the general consensus is there, the opportunity is there, the intention is there, and the lack of a serious, serious immediate consequence / detailed threat from China is there. I really think if the threat were made clearer, the US would be more drastic in stopping Pelosi and I would expect a lot of internal conflict within government regarding the decision to go.

Spicing up the odds upon learning that CNN also reported what a Taiwanese media outlet reported. Plus, the Taiwanese report is detailed enough that I think it provides enough resolution to lean this toward yes. Couple these with the fact Pelosi hasn't denied anything yet. Plus the intention remains. My personal view is she is really a person who doesn't care about consequences as long as it is right in her eyes. If Chinese consequences are at the price of freedom and democracy, which she believes very much, she is willing to pay for these.

"SET News said it was quoting Radio France Internationale (RFI) 'sources,' but did not elaborate, provide links, or indeed any other evidence. It said Pelosi will travel to Taiwan from Clark International Airport in the Philippines on Thursday (Aug.4).
Taiwan news reporting she will visit tomorrow night

Updating forecast: my previous forecast had some timing assumption wrong. It looks like that after mid-term election in Nov N. Pelosi will terminate her mandate (Democrats expected to loose elections). This decrease likelihood of trip / announcement between 1 Nov and 31 Dec. I'd still think that, if she was to act ratinally, she would not trigger Chinese with this trip, thus the unchanged higher likelihood of not before 1 Jan (55%). Same reasoning as before, trip discouraged by defense etc. However, emotional / behavioral factors made me reassess likelihood of a trip during the current Asian trip (hence, 28 July to 31 August now at slightly more than 1 in 3 times). Being 81, she might retire after this mandate and a trip to Taiwan might be some sort of legacy for her. In the past N. Pelosi did some bold move in terms of China US relations: "In September 1991, when I was CNN’s China bureau chief, then-U.S. Rep. Nancy Pelosi got me arrested. On a trip to Beijing with a congressional delegation, one of her colleagues alerted me that Pelosi and two other congressmen were planning to slip away from their official escorts and visit Tiananmen Square. But I was not told that her plan was, with news cameras rolling, to hold up a banner and lay flowers to commemorate students killed when the Chinese army crushed pro-democracy demonstrators there two years earlier.. "

"Speaker Nancy Pelosi began a fraught tour of Asia on Sunday that administration officials say they now expect will include a stop in Taiwan, despite China’s increasingly sharp warnings in recent days that a visit to the self-governing island would provoke a response, perhaps a military one."
I think she is there. I do not think she'll announce it though. about 4.45

I think it's on, I give it still 6% there is a last minute change of plan and 5% that they just keep the meeting secret indefinitely

I guess another way to look at this question is how often and how willing is American government to tolerate likely consequences/responses by the Chinese government? I'm pretty sure China wouldn't nuke DC because of Pelosi trotting around Taiwan. I'm pretty sure China wouldn't declare war or immediately say, "Mine!" and invade Taiwan the next week. The likely response would be some gray zone that is totally expected yet tolerable by the US government only because it isn't extreme.

Washington Post reporter says the trip is on: https://twitter.com/PostLive/status/1553013067356725248
We would be living in a rational world if people made rational decisions.

Washington Post reporter's assertion seems backed by US diplomatic sources. I think that after the Biden-Xi call on the 28th, if diplomatic sources say that the trip is on, there is very little that is going to change the speaker's mind. Pelosi's office saying the trip is possible but not confirmed would be in line with their policy of not confirming trips ahead of time hence doesn't inform the forecast.

I just checked the House schedule: https://rollcall.com/2021/11/30/house-unveils-2022-calendar/ Pelosi has two windows of opportunity to go on a trip: this next month and then again in October. I am therefore moving the November-December bucket to a very low probability.
Washington Post reporter says the trip is on: https://twitter.com/PostLive/status/1553013067356725248

https://www.cnn.com/2022/07/29/politics/nancy-pelosi-asia-trip-taiwan/index.htmlShe is setting off on her trip, and refusing to deny that she will visit Taiwan. If it is going to come out eventually that she didn't go, why not say it now?
Paraphrased snippet from NPR: With elections slated for November, neither party is interested in appearing to bow to China.
A couple of news pieces out today. Some of the reporting might be relevant here.
Every politician telling her to go is a Republican. Random example:
"It remains unclear whether the U.S. House speaker and an accompanying group of Democrat lawmakers intend to stop by Japan before or after a possible trip to Taiwan."

I am unfortunately out of touch with the current US political climate. If (according to the sources) there was no such visit for a House speaker in 25 years, then the probability is quite low, but it cannot be completely ruled out that it won't happen.
It will likely not be before mid term elections and until after the holiday season as constraints to shipping will want to be avoided.

Such a trip provides a grand total of zero advantage to anybody, including Her Imperial Speakership. Ordinarily this would make it a sure thing, but at this particular moment even she may discern this and postpone again. And again. And again.
https://www.nytimes.com/2022/07/25/us/politics/china-taiwan-biden-pelosi.html

Pelosi sees Taiwan as independent from China so they are a separate entity and deservingly so. That's going to be a strong belief to shake off from someone like Pelosi. She wants in on the cake. She doesn't believe the cake is China's.

Pelosi needs to balance the risk of provocation against the risk of appearing to cave in. Seems like a badly planned itinerary. (And I wonder how it would have been had someone as high-ranking as Pelosi announced that she'd suddenly visited Taiwan.)

Seems to be a distinct possibility. It's not like US lawmakers don't visit Taiwan all the time, btw: https://www.voanews.com/a/us-lawmakers-declare-solidarity-with-taiwan-in-controversial-trip-/6531683.html China never reacts well, either.

So Xi Ping and Biden will have their virtual meeting on the 28th July. Nothing will happen before that. Both Pentagon and Biden seems to be against raising tension with China. i tilt therefore toward this trip not happening any time soon. China just made clear a trip would trigger them (BBG article "china getting seriously prepared for pelosi visit to taiwan" Zhao statements. Travelling for August has been already planned ( Japan, Singapore, Indonesia and Malaysia ) so unlikely to appen (odds 1 out of 20). 1/9 to 31/10 is two month as opposed to just one so should at least being as likely August if not twice as likely. Same for 1/11 to 31/12. November to Dec slightly more likley as more fwd in time so more p of easing tension (whishfulk thinking? ).

Given that it's a multi-nation trip in August, I'm not sure whether it will be say August 20 to 31, then she gets back to US soil, then announces she's in Taiwan. However, it's more likely now that I think about it that if she lands in Taiwan, reports will be quite immediate, so a delay in reporting shouldn't be weighed heavily.

I think she probably has to go at this point; I feel like the gauntlet was thrown down and she might need to go in order to save face/preserve global reputation. According to the leak, the trip was planned for August, I think buckets 2 and 3 are most likely; I can see her announcing her trip after the fact, but I'm not sure what she gains by waiting a long time to announce that a trip took place.
Possibility: visits at the very end of August, discloses it took place a few days later, in September

I wouldn't take Biden's comment that it's a bad idea at face value because he has a habit of saying random things to the press that don't hold up. I don't see her going after November because finishing up business in Congress before the next term is probably more important at that point. I could see a postponement from August to Oct/Nov happening but if it gets postponed a second time, most likely just won't happen in the question period
she will likely cancel her visit

These kinds of visits have happened before and we're still not in a nuclear war. Pelosi has visited war-torn Ukraine this year on a surprise visit. She said she would earlier this year. And the US mid-term elections make it much more tempting for such a visit prior to November. In previous two times, the two visits happened in April and in November. Hmmm. Biden seems to disagree with Pelosi's ambitions to visit Taiwan at this time.
Whole host of reasons. Much depending on J-6 and how this begins to swing to favor the Democrats. If November of '22 looks really good for them, she may go just before.
